				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/communism-will-win" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(617958); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=617958&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182737" alt="Communism will win" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=617958)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/communism-will-win" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(617958); return false;" >Communism will win</a></span> <span class="odate time_1389420288 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Jan 2014 06:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1933151">
									

<p>Pretty much whenever you're writing an in-universe report for the wiki, it's very likely to incorporate Things The Reader Doesn't Get To Know &#8212; stuff that, rather than providing the reader specific information about the anomaly in question or about the organization in question, is just there to give you a sense that something is happening or that things are done some way. They're meant to convey the mood or tone, rather than actual content.</p>
<p>Because the Foundation and GOC formats are different types of storytelling (albeit in the same rough genre), it's okay for TTRDGTK to be different for each format.</p>
<p>At least, that's my take on it.</p>

							</div>

