				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-reach" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1779895); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1779895&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182737" alt="Dr Reach" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1779895)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-reach" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1779895); return false;" >Dr Reach</a></span> <span class="odate time_1389547900 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">12 Jan 2014 17:31</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1934205">
									

<p><sub>Correct me if I'm wrong, but I feel Denvers come from a different point in our own timeline, while Ragweed come from a different timeline altogether. What might that imply and how to distinguish them may be <em>tricky</em> in universe.</sub> (What Dark Lord Derpy said up there.)</p>
<p>Questions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Does a Freud-artifact include memetic, cognitohazardous and perception-altering entities?</li>
<li>What about items entirely or partially made up of information, such as whatever came through <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2998">SCP-2998</a>? Would they be considered</li>
<li>What about extraterrestrial entities? Are they called <em>Fiji</em> by default? (Recommending a new Non-Humanoid class type.)</li>
<li>Since the GOC has access to nanotech, should we consider a sub class that goes/exists between Moro and Artifact?</li>
</ul>
<p>Thinking up modifiers, entities able to cause specific cognitohazards could be marked as such in their code, so people reading them were aware of the special precautions that had to be made about them. Reds and Greens have their classes, but cognitos may happen in combination with all humanoid, non-humanoid, artifact and (especially) organization classes, wouldn't they? So, it might be useful to mark them as modifiers.</p>
<p>Although, if we create so many modifiers we are effectively putting tags in every codename, some codenames will be too long. : /</p>
<p>Anyways, I like this a lot. : D</p>

							</div>

								
